To get the token properties from the token address, you first need to interact with the ERC20 contract at that address. Here's a breakdown of the steps to get the token properties:

1. Define the ERC20 token ABI:

```javascript
const erc20ABI = [
  "function name() view returns (string)",
  "function symbol() view returns (string)",
  "function decimals() view returns (uint8)",
];
```

2. Create a function to fetch token properties:

```javascript
async function getTokenProperties(tokenAddress) {
  const tokenContract = new ethers.Contract(tokenAddress, erc20ABI, provider);
  const [name, symbol, decimals] = await Promise.all([
    tokenContract.name(),
    tokenContract.symbol(),
    tokenContract.decimals(),
  ]);

  return {
    name,
    symbol,
    decimals,
  };
}
```

3. Use the `getTokenProperties` function to get the properties of the tokens:

```javascript
const test = async () => {
  try {
    // ...

    const tokenToSwapProperties = await getTokenProperties(tokenToSwapAddress);
    console.log('Token to swap properties:', tokenToSwapProperties);
    const tokenToReceiveProperties = await getTokenProperties(tokenToReceiveAddress);
    console.log('Token to receive properties:', tokenToReceiveProperties);

    const tokenToSwap = new Token(
      1,
      tokenToSwapAddress,
      tokenToSwapProperties.decimals,
      tokenToSwapProperties.symbol,
      tokenToSwapProperties.name
    );

    const tokenToReceive = new Token(
      1,
      tokenToReceiveAddress,
      tokenToReceiveProperties.decimals,
      tokenToReceiveProperties.symbol,
      tokenToReceiveProperties.name
    );

  } catch (e) {
    console.log(e);
  }
};
test();
```

This code will fetch the token properties (name, symbol, and decimals) for the addresses you've provided and then create `Token` instances using those properties.
